## 2. Lists

A **list** in R is a flexible container that can hold mixed kinds of values, including vectors, strings, numbers, booleans, and even other lists. The R docs and introductory materials describe lists as a recursive, general-purpose structure. ([CRAN][3])

```r
user_profile <- list("Anthony", 32, TRUE)
print(user_profile)
```

Named list:

```r
book <- list(
  title = "Apple",
  author = "Steve Jobs",
  pages = 549
)

print(book)
print(book$title)
```

This is the closest base-R equivalent to a dictionary/object for many beginner tasks.

---

## 3. Factors

A **factor** represents categorical data. Introductory R materials emphasize factors when you want a discrete variable for analysis. ([CRAN][4])

```r
roles <- factor(c("viewer", "editor", "admin", "viewer"))
print(roles)
```

Factors are especially useful when categories matter analytically, not just as plain text.

Example:

```r
membership_level <- factor(c("bronze", "silver", "gold", "silver"))
print(membership_level)
```

This is more R/statistics-oriented than what you saw in Python or Go.

---

## 4. Data frames

A **data frame** is one of the most important structures in R. The official docs say `data.frame()` creates tightly coupled collections of variables and that data frames are the fundamental data structure for much of R’s modeling software. The language definition also describes a data frame as a list of equal-length vectors/factors/matrices. ([Seminar for Statistics][5])

```r
student <- data.frame(
  name = "Mike",
  age = 32,
  active = TRUE
)

print(student)
```

Multiple rows:

```r
students <- data.frame(
  name = c("Mike", "Ava", "Jordan"),
  age = c(32, 28, 35),
  active = c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE)
)

print(students)
```

Access a column:

```r
print(students$name)
print(students$age)
```

Add a column:

```r
students$city <- c("Bowie", "DC", "Baltimore")
print(students)
```

### Compare to PostgreSQL

A data frame feels a lot like a small in-memory table.

